Match-case — structural pattern matching from three point ten.

Python three point ten added match-case — its take on a switch statement, with structural patterns over the matched value. The patterns can match literals like case zero. Match shapes like case bracket a b bracket matches any two-element sequence, or case brace key colon v matches a dict with that key. Match types like case int parens. Bind values with the matched parts like case point of x and y. Use the pipe operator for or-patterns like case zero pipe one. Use a guard like case x if x greater-than zero. And the underscore is the wildcard — matches anything, binds nothing.

This is not just switch with patterns. The case clauses can destructure deeply. It rewards reading carefully, because the cases that look like variable references are sometimes patterns.

In code, picture def day-name taking n integer returning string. Match n — case zero returns monday, case one returns tuesday, case two returns wednesday, case three pipe four returns later in the week, case underscore returns weekend.

Structural matching — destructure a dict. Def describe taking an event dict. Match event — case brace type colon click, target colon target close brace returns click on target. Case brace type colon key, key colon k close brace returns key pressed. Case brace type colon scroll, amount colon amt close brace, if amt greater-than zero, returns scrolled down by amt. Case underscore returns unknown event.

Class patterns — destructure attributes. From data-classes import data-class. At data-class. Class point with fields x and y. Def quadrant taking a point returning string. Match p — case point of zero zero returns origin. Case point of x zero returns on x-axis at x. Case point of zero y returns on y-axis at y. Then four cases with guards for the four quadrants based on sign of x and y.
